        <h2>Pricing comparison</h2>

        <h3>Stack</h3>
        <p>Stack pricing starts around $2,999/year for the core estimating tier. Team and enterprise pricing varies based on users and modules. Stack's pricing reflects its positioning as a premium commercial estimating platform — it's designed for mid-to-large commercial estimating teams where the productivity gains justify the investment.</p>

        <h3>PlanSwift</h3>
        <p>PlanSwift offers both subscription (~$1,749/year) and perpetual license (~$1,749 one-time). The perpetual option is genuinely compelling for contractors who want to own their tools — buy once, use indefinitely. Annual maintenance after the perpetual purchase is optional. For small firms with limited software budgets, the perpetual option provides a lower total cost of ownership over 3–5 years.</p>

        <h2>Where Stack wins</h2>

        <h3>Team collaboration on large bids</h3>
        <p>Stack's biggest advantage is real-time collaboration. When multiple estimators are working on a large commercial bid — one doing MEP, another doing structural, a third doing architectural finishes — Stack lets them work simultaneously on the same plan set without file version confusion. The team view shows who's measuring what in real time, preventing duplicate work and scope gaps.</p>

        <p>PlanSwift is fundamentally a single-user desktop application. You can share files via Dropbox or similar, but two estimators can't work on the same file simultaneously without risking data conflicts. For commercial estimating teams doing bids over $10M, Stack's collaboration model is a significant workflow improvement.</p>

        <h3>Plan management and distribution</h3>
        <p>Stack includes plan management as a core feature — upload plan sets, manage revisions, and distribute plans to your estimating team or subcontractors, all from within the platform. PlanSwift expects you to manage plan files externally (local drive, Dropbox, etc.) and import them for measuring. For organizations receiving plan sets from architects and distributing them to subs, Stack's integrated plan management saves administrative time.</p>

        <h3>Bid management layer</h3>
        <p>Stack goes beyond takeoff into bid management — tracking which subcontractors you've solicited, which have responded, and organizing your bid submission. PlanSwift is purely a measurement and estimating tool; you'd need separate tools or manual processes for bid solicitation and tracking. For GCs doing formal bid submissions to owners, Stack's bid management tools create a more complete workflow.</p>

        <h3>Modern interface</h3>
        <p>Stack's UI is modern and browser-based. PlanSwift's interface was designed over a decade ago and shows its age. For estimators who care about working in a clean, contemporary tool, Stack is the better experience. This sounds superficial, but tools that are pleasant to use get used more consistently.</p>

        <h2>Where PlanSwift wins</h2>

        <h3>Assembly system depth</h3>
        <p>PlanSwift's assembly system is more configurable than Stack's. Estimators who've built detailed assemblies over years — specific waste factors, labor units, material pricing structures — find PlanSwift more flexible. The ability to build completely custom assemblies for any trade workflow, with unlimited item nesting, gives experienced estimators more control over their estimating model.</p>

        <h3>Excel integration</h3>
        <p>PlanSwift can live-link measurements to Excel cells, allowing estimators to take a measurement in PlanSwift and have it automatically populate in a corresponding Excel model. For estimating departments that have spent years building Excel bid templates they don't want to abandon, this integration is a genuine differentiator. Stack exports to Excel but doesn't maintain a live bidirectional link.</p>

        <h3>Perpetual license and offline capability</h3>
        <p>PlanSwift runs fully offline and can be purchased as a perpetual license. For contractors in areas with unreliable internet, or who prefer to own their tools, these are meaningful advantages. Stack requires internet access and is subscription-only — no exceptions.</p>

        <h3>Cost for small shops</h3>
        <p>At ~$1,749/year (or as a one-time purchase), PlanSwift costs significantly less than Stack for a single-user or two-user estimating operation. If you don't need the collaboration or plan management features that justify Stack's premium, PlanSwift delivers more value per dollar for small teams.</p>

        <h2>The workflow question</h2>
        <p>The more useful lens for this comparison is workflow, not features:</p>

        <p><strong>Choose Stack if your estimating process looks like this:</strong> Multiple estimators, large commercial bids, formal bid submission to owners, need to distribute plan sets to subs, require version control on plans, and operate in an environment where internet access is reliable.</p>

        <p><strong>Choose PlanSwift if your estimating process looks like this:</strong> Solo or small-team estimating, multi-trade flexibility, existing Excel models you want to preserve, prefer to own your software, or work in environments where internet reliability is uncertain.</p>

        <h2>Bottom line</h2>
        <p>Stack is the better tool for commercial estimating teams that collaborate on large bids. PlanSwift is the better tool for solo estimators, small shops, and contractors who value the perpetual license option and deep Excel integration. Most contractors doing both residential and commercial estimating with a small team land on PlanSwift; commercial GCs with dedicated estimating departments lean toward Stack.</p>

